<paper id="1513521852"><title>Algebraic Attacks on Summation Generators</title><year>2004</year><authors><author org="National Security Research Institute" id="2597267034">Dong Hoon Lee</author><author org="National Security Research Institute" id="2110537135">Jaeheon Kim</author><author org="National Security Research Institute" id="2122029728">Jin Hong</author><author org="National Security Research Institute" id="2148808328">Jae Woo Han</author><author org="National Security Research Institute" id="2131345726">Dukjae Moon</author></authors><n_citation>43</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1699105</reference><reference>1520563459</reference><reference>1542020576</reference><reference>1546392762</reference><reference>1560023496</reference><reference>1569499052</reference><reference>1572961947</reference><reference>1573095851</reference><reference>1582711866</reference><reference>2087189997</reference><reference>2146561088</reference></references><venue id="2758283624" type="C">Fast Software Encryption</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-25937-4_3</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.62126">Pairwise summation</keyword><keyword weight="0.46951">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.46279">Shift register</keyword><keyword weight="0.46201">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.52539">Algebraic number</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Linear feedback shift register</keyword><keyword weight="0.4758">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.53559">Upper and lower bounds</keyword><keyword weight="0.55892">Algebraic equation</keyword><keyword weight="0.52289">Stream cipher</keyword><keyword weight="0.42492">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We apply the algebraic attacks on stream ciphers with memories to the summation generator. For a summation generator that uses n LFSRs, an algebraic equation relating the key stream bits and LFSR output bits can be made to be of degree less than 